 Conversely, let 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 be a point in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{N}(k)$
\end_inset

 with coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{i,j}$
\end_inset

 that satisfy the given equations.
 At least one of these coordinates must be non-zero; we can assume without
 loss of generality that it is 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{0,0}$
\end_inset

.
 Let us pass to affine coordinates by setting 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{0,0}=1$
\end_inset

.
 Then we have 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{i,j}=z_{i,0}z_{0,j}$
\end_inset

; so by setting 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}=z_{i,0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{j}=z_{0,j}$
\end_inset

 we obtain a point 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)\times\mathbb{P}^{m}(k)$
\end_inset

 that is mapped to 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Continuing the above notation, let 
\begin_inset Formula $z\in f(\mathbb{P}^{n}(k)\times\mathbb{P}^{m}(k))$
\end_inset

 be a point with 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{0,0}=1$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x,y)=z$
\end_inset

, it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}\neq0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{0}\neq0$
\end_inset

, so we can assume 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{0}=1$
\end_inset

 as the 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{j}$
\end_inset

 are only determined up to a common scalar.
 But then it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}=z_{i,0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{j}=z_{0,j}$
\end_inset

